00:55:03.160 --> 00:55:05.430
We've got a better handle
than we have elsewhere,

00:55:05.430 --> 00:55:07.090
but we've got much,
much more to do.

00:55:07.090 --> 00:55:09.910
And the next phases, we'll
be looking at key foundation

00:55:09.910 --> 00:55:13.160
species, genomic variation
within those species,

00:55:13.160 --> 00:55:16.930
and their microbial
associates and the interaction

00:55:16.930 --> 00:55:18.860
between those.

00:55:18.860 --> 00:55:21.257
We can't stop.

00:55:21.257 --> 00:55:22.840
We have the scale
of the island, which

00:55:22.840 --> 00:55:24.890
we're trying to understand
and model what's

00:55:24.890 --> 00:55:26.930
happening inside the island.

00:55:26.930 --> 00:55:29.300
But we have to take all of
the external inputs, which

00:55:29.300 --> 00:55:31.510
at least we can measure,
because in an island,

00:55:31.510 --> 00:55:33.860
we know what's outside and
what's inside our system.

00:55:33.860 --> 00:55:35.930
The drivers from
outside, we're there

00:55:35.930 --> 00:55:37.800
taking regional
and global models

00:55:37.800 --> 00:55:39.700
and downscaling those
and linking them

00:55:39.700 --> 00:55:41.910
to our local models.

00:55:41.910 --> 00:55:44.550
So we're not ignoring what's
happening at the larger

00:55:44.550 --> 00:55:48.470
scale and different
time scales, but having

00:55:48.470 --> 00:55:52.090
to integrate that with what's
happening at the local scale.

00:55:52.090 --> 00:55:54.840
So I didn't mean to
imply that we're only

00:55:54.840 --> 00:55:57.390
doing the larger species
and ignoring the microbes.

00:55:57.390 --> 00:55:59.950
And the global
changes, we absolutely

00:55:59.950 --> 00:56:01.450
have to take into account.

00:56:01.450 --> 00:56:03.700
But the predictive
models are basically,

00:56:03.700 --> 00:56:05.200
can we predict what
this island will

00:56:05.200 --> 00:56:11.470
look like in a few decades
under likely scenarios

00:56:11.470 --> 00:56:14.360
of environmental change-- that's
one of the simulations we want

00:56:14.360 --> 00:56:19.340
to run-- and under likely
scenarios of policy

00:56:19.340 --> 00:56:23.860
change and, of course, the
interaction between those two?

00:56:23.860 --> 00:56:26.450
So we're not trying to simulate
every possible scenario.

00:56:26.450 --> 00:56:29.140
We're trying to simulate a small
number of scenarios that are

00:56:29.140 --> 00:56:33.410
relevant and hopefully useful.

